Figured out:
readline - send a string, readline will create a shell-like prompt, returns the line sent by user
add_history - send a string, adds that string to readline's history (during prompt, can access history with keybinds)
rl_clear_history - clear the readline history (no args)
wait3 - like wait, but with the possibiity of sending a rusage struct to be filled - requires getrusage to be used, which isn't an allowed function..??
wait4 - like waitpid, same as wait3
getcwd - get current working directory, send buffer address and its size
chdir - change current working directory, takes the absolute path (we'll have to build it ourselves I guess)
stat - get file stats (not sure yet what for) in a struct stat structure
lstat - get file stats but if the file is a symlink, get stats of the link file, not where it points
opendir, readdir, closedir - allows reading directory contents (their files), not sure what for yet
isatty - use to know whether file descriptor refers to a terminal (don't know what this is used for)
ttyname, ttyslot - used to get the name of the tty (by fd) or slot of the current tty (no arg), no idea what this is for


